        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The essential requirements to fulfill our scientific goal are as follows. 
(1) Simultaneous observations of 12CO, HDO, and H2O2;
(2) High spatial resolution in order to resolve the Mars-disk for global-mapping, and to resolve limb of the Martian atmosphere for wind measurements;
(3) High sensitivity in order to retrieve temperature profile with high precision (~ 5 K), water vapor at middle altitudes from Nadir-viewing, and in order to search weak signals of H2O2;
ALMA band-7 with its Cycle-2 specification is the only facility to satisfy all of these requirements. 

This is a ToO observation: 
The trigger of observation is the occurrence of global dust storm on Mars.  
The observation is triggered to carry out when (1) Optical depth at visible wavelength exceeds 2.0 and (2) area of the dust storm expands over a half of Martian disk. 
See the Science Justification for the detail of the trigger. 

During the ALMA-Cycle2 period, the possible seasons to observe global dust storms correspond to the period between August/2014 and May/2015. 
The diameter of Mars ranges between 4" and 7" during this period. 
In order to obtain global-maps and wind velocity from limb of the atmosphere, we require a synthesis beam size smaller than 0.125 x apparent disk size (the smallest case is 0.5" for 4"-disk). 
Note that the maximum apparent disk size of Mars is within the maximum recoverable scale of 12-m array, thus ACA array is not needed.

The target lines in our observations are as follows: 12CO 345.795 GHz, HDO 335.539 GHz, and H2O2 335.560 GHz. 
For owing to the large IF of ALMA receiver, the band-7 can measure theses lines simultaneously. 
For CO, we propose the high resolution correlator (122 kHz) to retrieve wind velocity with precision of 12m/s. 
For HDO and H2O2, we propose the 282 KHz resolution to resolve the narrow lines. 
In addition, we need one broad-bandwidth (~800 MHz) to obtain the full spectral features of 12CO and HDO. 

Most stringent sensititivity requirements in our science objectives is to retrieve wind velocity with a precision of 12 m/s. 
To measure the wind with this precision, 0.22 Kelvin (244 kHz-resolution) is required for 12CO line mapping. 
In the present proposal we estimated the observation time with the worst condition (0.5" synthesis beam), and got the total estimated observation time including calibration data acquisition as 1.56 hr. 

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
